@Cluny_the_Rat @mdudas @farokh @CryptoMories @opensea With emphasis that the initiator, *under threat of perjury*, believes in good faith that the material in question is infringing upon their owned IP.

This is going to be an evolving, ongoing conversation thatâ€™s been most recently sparked by current events, but likely wonâ€™t find a firm resolution. Iâ€™m very curious to hear othersâ€™ thoughts here. If youâ€™ve made it this far, thank you for entertaining my rambling musings

I also think we should place a distinctions between falling short of expectations and outright deceptive marketing practices, blatant SEC/securities violations & fraud. 
Many projects/businesses *will* fail. Whether or not they had malicious intent is another beast entirely.

While I believe thereâ€™s a level of personal responsibility involved (naivety & willful ignorance are certainly factors), I think thereâ€™s a lot left to be desired towards better educating those that we onboard of the inherent risks of self-custody and a volatile, illiquid market.

I believe that participation in a decentralized, self-sovereign, unregulated market comes with an assumption of risk that many do not seem to recognize. We talk about â€œDYORâ€ and â€œdue diligenceâ€ when many do not understand what research that entails to better protect themselves.

Thereâ€™s a lot of discussion around regulation, consumer protections, and potential avenues of recourse off the back of the Pixelmon situation. 
Itâ€™s a complex, nuanced conversation that can be viewed from many angles.

@HawkwardArt @DeezeFi or potentially lose their safe harbor protections & be liable for damages themselves, yes. DMCA is the law outlining the process. 
- DMCA notice
- Online Service Provider removes content
- Notify user
- User provides counter-notice
- OSP restores access or initiate court action

The market doesnâ€™t properly value or reward the front-loading of these expenses so most projects donâ€™t bother. As the space matures, buyers should be asking better questions and founders expecting higher levels of scrutiny (general retail doing better research)

As buyers become more reluctant to blindly throw their crypto at random projects & unproven teams, I believe there will be an opportunity in providing further transparency & additional assurances (disclosures, 3rd party contract audits, security consulting, locked liquidity, etc)
